---
title: "R Markdown"
---




You can include R Markdown files in your project.

## R Markdown

This is an R Markdown document. Markdown is a simple formatting syntax for authoring HTML, PDF, and MS Word documents. For more details on using R Markdown see <http://rmarkdown.rstudio.com>.

When you click the **Knit** button a document will be generated that includes both content as well as the output of any embedded R code chunks within the document. You can embed an R code chunk like this:


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
summary(cars)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}
```
     speed           dist       
 Min.   : 4.0   Min.   :  2.00  
 1st Qu.:12.0   1st Qu.: 26.00  
 Median :15.0   Median : 36.00  
 Mean   :15.4   Mean   : 42.98  
 3rd Qu.:19.0   3rd Qu.: 56.00  
 Max.   :25.0   Max.   :120.00  
```
:::
:::


## Including Plots

You can also embed plots and reference them, like so @fig-pressure.


::: {.cell}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![Plot of pressure](rmarkdown_files/figure-html/fig-pressure-1.png){#fig-pressure width=672}
:::
:::


Note that the `echo = FALSE` parameter was added to the code chunk to prevent printing of the R code that generated the plot.

## Including Tables

You can also embed tables and reference them with @tbl-iris.


::: {#tbl-iris .cell tbl-cap='Iris Data'}

```{.r .cell-code}
library(knitr)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr}
```
Warning: package 'knitr' was built under R version 4.3.1
```
:::

```{.r .cell-code}
kable(head(iris))
```
